<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Convergence day. Six blocks of work funnel into one artifact.</p>
  <p>Until today you've been building pieces: factors in Block 1, subsystems in Block 2, Mars failure modes in Block 3, scale in Block 4, detection methods in Block 5, and your chosen exoplanet in Block 6. Today those pieces become one document — the Habitability Framework — and that document becomes the spine of the <a href="/units/unit-1/assessment-goldilocks-report/">Goldilocks Report</a> you'll draft in Block 8 and defend in Block 10.</p>
  <p>The framework template asks five questions of every criterion you propose: <strong>(1)</strong> name it precisely, <strong>(2)</strong> say why it matters for life, <strong>(3)</strong> say how a scientist would detect it from data, <strong>(4)</strong> give Earth's value as the baseline, and <strong>(5)</strong> name where this criterion can fail. The five-field structure is deliberate — it forces every criterion to be specific, detectable, and justified. "Has the right environment" doesn't survive the template. "Stable surface temperature range allowing liquid water" does.</p>
  <p>That last field — <em>where it can fail</em> — is the systems-thinking move from Block 2 in disguise. Asking what breaks when a criterion is absent is asking which feedback loop unwinds. Mars's atmosphere didn't disappear at once; an atmospheric-loss feedback ran unchecked once the magnetic field weakened. Every criterion you write today is also a claim about a feedback loop that keeps life possible.</p>
</section>

